# Relay System Rules

Read `docs/RELAY_SYSTEM.md` before making relay changes.

## Stack

```
CybinRelayPool (transport) → RelayConnectionStateMachine (lifecycle)
  → SubscriptionMultiplexer (dedup/merge) → Repositories (consumers)
```

## Subscription Rules

- Always go through `SubscriptionMultiplexer` — never create raw WebSocket subscriptions from repositories
- Multiplexer uses filter merging + ref-counting. CLOSE only fires when last consumer unsubscribes.
- 5 priority tiers: CRITICAL(4) > HIGH(3) > NORMAL(2) > LOW(1) > BACKGROUND(0)
- Higher priority can preempt lowest-priority EOSE'd subscription
- MAX_SUBS_PER_RELAY = 40

## Connection Management

- `RelayConnectionStateMachine` uses TinderStateMachine: Disconnected → Connecting → Connected → Subscribed → ConnectFailed
- Reconnect: exponential backoff 2s→30s, 6 attempts, 8/wave with 600ms stagger
- Circuit breaker: 5min blacklist after exhausting reconnect attempts
- Keepalive: 2min check, 5min stale threshold

## Health Tracking

- `RelayHealthTracker` scores per-relay performance
- Auto-blocks relay after 5 consecutive failures
- Adaptive limit reduction on NOTICE/CLOSED rate-limit (min 3 subs)

## NIP-65 Outbox

- `Nip65RelayListRepository` resolves kind-10002 write relays
- `OutboxFeedManager` uses Thompson Sampling for Bayesian relay ranking
- Preloads quoted note authors' write relays when thread opens

## Ktor Only

All HTTP and WebSocket uses Ktor CIO engine. Do NOT introduce OkHttp.
